On 8/12/20 7:47 PM, Larry McVoy wrote:
> The SMIT I had did*not*  show you what files it was editing

My recollection is that smit(ty) did /not/ show you the commands that=20
would be run /by/ /default/.

That being said, there was a (P)F key you could press prior to=20
executing, one of the many (P)F keys smit(ty) used, that would show you=20
the command and all of it's arguments which would be run.

I didn't like /using/ smit(ty) for much.  But I did find it /useful/ for =

learning things which I didn't know by using the menu a few times and=20
analyzing the command(s) that it would generate and run.

I think it was a really advanced form of "<bla> command example"=20
searches that I see people doing on the regular.  The BIG advantage is=20
that you used the menu interface to tweak parameters for your configurati=
on.

smit(ty) also had the added advantage that it could look up possible=20
values of things to put in the fields for you.

I don't know any seasoned AIX admins that use smit(ty) for their day to=20
day, week to week, or even month to month activities.  Though I think=20
many of them end up using smit(ty) once every year or two to look at a=20
particularly obtuse command.  Sort of like a contextual aware man page.



--=20
Grant. . . .
